				\begin{document}$$p\left(l,y\right)=\frac{y-{y}_{1}}{{y}_{2}-{y}_{1}} p\left(l,{y}_{1}\right)+\frac{{y}_{2}-y}{{y}_{2}-{y}_{1}}p\left(l,{y}_{2}\right).$$\end{document} If we have available data only on one side of the missing year, we use the country’s GDP as an auxiliary variable in the imputation. More specifically, people’s income/consumption is assumed to increase and decrease with GDP. Suppose that a country’s GDP rises by 5%. By our assumption, people’s income/consumption also increases by 5% in that country. We then impute missing values by calculating poverty estimates from the new income/consumption distribution.
